anings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":39,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":112,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Reade was born in 1343, in Devon, England. She had at least 1 son with Richard Talbot."},"et":{"1343–NN":"1343–Surnud","1340–1387":"1340–1387","1361–1449":"1361–1449","1343–Female":"1343–Surnud","1455":"1455","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","1340":"1340","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1449":"1449","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1343–NN":"1343–Kuollut","1340–1387":"1340–1387","1361–1449":"1361–1449","1343–Female":"1343–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1343":"1343","1387":"1387","1340":"1340","1361